title: For Sale:  Springfield 1911-A1 Mil-Spec Titanium Cerakote FS/FT
postcontent:
First off this was a refurbish project.  The gun was originally the standard bluing from the factory.  
1.  I had the entire gun blasted with Aluminum Oxide to give the slide and frame a very light texture and to remove any scratches or wear.  

2.  From there we treated all parts with Micro-Crystalline Zinc Phosphate and then had it professionally coated in Cerakote H.  The target range for Cerakote is between .5-1 mils and our average was .78 mils all over.  

3.  Finally we replaced the grips panels with milled/anodized dragon scale aluminum panels.

Micro-Crystalline Zinc Phosphate and Cerakote is the new Military Spec Coating proceedure and there are only a handful of places in the US that do both.

This pistol is absolutely beautiful.  the trigger pull is somewhere around 4 pounds and is very smooth.

title: For Sale:  Underwood M1 Carbine .30 cal
postcontent:
Edit: I am going to be at the gun show in Waukesha tomorrow with this rifle. I'll be easy to spot, I am 6'6" and have a goatee. Text me six 0 eight 556 seven one 68
Photos:
http://s1129.photobucket.com/albums/m509/itmustbeslim/M1/#!cpZZ1QQtppZZ20

The original assault rifle! I have for sale a well loved M1 Carbine. I have done all the research on it so never worry! It is a typical mix and match from the Korean war, though the receiver most likely saw service in Europe during world war 2. The receiver is an underwood receiver from late 1944, Inland low wood stock from Inland (hard to age) came from South Haven MI, has visible cartouche and OI marking. Magazine and ejector button are consistent with late WW2 service as well. This carbine has a wonderful Blue Sky barrel, verifiable to not not have stamp damage. Late WW2 band, and late WW2 shell deflector. No loss of parkerizing, no rust (though I have not verified under the barrel and action however. Good coloring and just an overall nice little rifle.
What else can I say? Straight shooter, I even sighted it in with some vintage ammo just before deer season and is still within milspec at 100 yards. I mean at only 35 1/2 inches, this is the perfect hallway gun.

What do I want to do with this rifle? I would like to sell it of course, cash is King and I don't typically hold rifles on promises of payment.

However I am very interested in trading for a few things: M1 Garands (remember though that they still have these at CMP in Ohio for 525 so must be about same value as I am asking) .308 Garand would be amazing as I would like to start mechanical sight competitions! I am also looking for a good semi auto pistol, prefer 9mm, let me know what you got. No Smith and Wessons or glocks, I like sigs, Springfield XDs, Berettas, and the new walther if you got it. Bonus: I have been looking for a Browning Hi Power for a long time, I would add cash for one of these.
But don't let my list discourage you, send me an email and make me an offer!

Bonus, Bonus. Have you seen .30 cal ammo for sale? Me neither, you can't hardly get in anywhere. But I have just over 200 rounds that I can put with this rifle to make a deal. In this market that is over 100 bucks worth of ammo. In fact for you collectors, 200 of the rounds are still in original issue strippers, inside military boxes and Viet Nam era OD green pouch belt (pictured).

I have a valid WI CW permit, no felons, must be WI resident, prefer bill of sale but am flexible.
